fields.name: column
fields.description:
The index of the column to which this result group belongs. The column
definitions and capabilities will eventually be specified by the query;
however, for now we say that:

1) two columns are allowed.
2) 0 is the left (primary) column.
3) 1 is the right-hand (secondary) column.

Also, we consider this a hint, so the UI is free to ignore if it doesn't
make sense to use it; that is, for mobile or if the user reduces their
browser size.

If the column is null, it's assumed to be 0.

fields.name: foldHint
fields.description:
A hint for which results in this result group are important enough to
place above the fold. This is a 0-indexed result list; "0" means show
1 result (fold after result index 0), "4" means show 5 results (fold
after result index 4), etc.
The UI is free to ignore this if it doesn't make sense to use it.
foldHint will be an index into ResultGroup.result

types.name: SearchExpArgs
types.description:
Contains experimental search parameters -- construct a new input variable
for each set of new experiments you'd like to try and include whatever
variables you'd like! Please document what your fields/inputs are for below:

ExptID: This specifies which experiment to use (the definitions for which
  can be found in fedsearch/mixer/bumblebee/service.go). If left blank/nil, we will
  instead use the feature flag value for this.
ContextID: This is an opaque handle that a client can pass in to retrieve past
  context stored on previous requests. How the experiment stores context relevant
  the ContextID is up to the implementer.
BumblebeeIgnoreSearchQueryCache: This specifies whether a Bumblebee search request
  should ignore a cached response (if one exists) and instead compute a fresh one.
  One application of setting this flag is to see how outputs change across multiple
  queries due to the randomness in GPT-3 decoding.

Value for a setting. The rules for a setting value are as follows:

* Each entry in SettingValue corresponds to a SettingType.

* The name should reflect the SettingType (e.g., if the SettingType
  is "String", then the field should be called "stringValue")

* Each field is nullable.

* Only the field with the appropriate value should be non-null.

* The field with the appropriate value should always be non-null.

Essentially, this is an implicit union. We don't use union semantics
since unions can't be used in input types (see
https://github.com/graphql/graphql-spec/issues/488), and we want loading and
setting Settings to be symmetric.

types.name: InteractionV3Type
types.description:
The collection of action types for the v3 interactions table.

Be VERY CAREFUL about extending the action types here. In general, we want
to have a very limited number of action types. If you need more information
about the context of an action, consider using Element, ElementAction, or
the Attributes table.

PLEASE KEEP IN SYNC with //schemas/constants/interaction_type.go.

enumValues.name: Click
enumValues.description:
Click covers all outbound clicks, i.e. anything that takes you outside of
neeva.

enumValues.name: View
enumValues.description:
View represents a view, according to the definition we've set (e.g. may or
may not be delayed).

enumValues.name: InternalClick
enumValues.description:
InternalClick represents a non-outbound click, and involves
the user interacting with some semantically meaningful part of a widget that
does not cause the user to leave the search context. Usually this is
something like navigating a carousel, showing more information, or seeing a
preview. Excludes MetaClicks.

enumValues.name: MetaClick
enumValues.description:
MetaClick represents a non-outbound click, and involves the
user interacting with a search element that changes the users relationship
to that element. This can be hide, follow, add to space, etc. Unlike an
InternalClick, a MetaClick does not involve the user interacting with the
element in a way that provides more information to the user.

enumValues.name: Refinement
enumValues.description:
Refinement is an interaction that initiates another, related search context,
i.e. by applying a corpus filter or opening a related search.

types.name: InteractionV3Category
types.description:
InteractionV3Category specifies the type of the item in the log tree hierarchy.
The log tree can have have N number of entries, but these are the ones
that have IDs associated.

PLEASE KEEP IN SYNC with //schemas/constants/category.go

enumValues.name: page
enumValues.description: Represents a page, such as a search results page or a space page.

enumValues.name: group
enumValues.description:
Represents a group of results or containers. This is synonymous with "result
group".

enumValues.name: container
enumValues.description: Represents a container of results, such as a news list or video carousel.

enumValues.name: result
enumValues.description:
Represents a single result. The result can be simple (a web link) or complex
(a rich entity), but this is the terminal category to which an action can
belong.

types.name: __Schema
types.description: A GraphQL Schema defines the capabilities of a GraphQL server. It exposes all available types and directives on the server, as well as the entry points for query, mutation, and subscription operations.

fields.name: types
fields.description: A list of all types supported by this server.

fields.name: queryType
fields.description: The type that query operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: mutationType
fields.description: If this server supports mutation, the type that mutation operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: subscriptionType
fields.description: If this server support subscription, the type that subscription operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: directives
fields.description: A list of all directives supported by this server.

types.name: __Type
types.description:
The fundamental unit of any GraphQL Schema is the type. There are many kinds of types in GraphQL as represented by the `__TypeKind` enum.

Depending on the kind of a type, certain fields describe information about that type. Scalar types provide no information beyond a name, description and optional `specifiedByUrl`, while Enum types provide their values. Object and Interface types provide the fields they describe. Abstract types, Union and Interface, provide the Object types possible at runtime. List and NonNull types compose other types.

types.name: __TypeKind
types.description: An enum describing what kind of type a given `__Type` is.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a scalar.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an object. `fields` and `interfaces` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an interface. `fields`, `interfaces`, and `possibleTypes` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: UNION
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a union. `possibleTypes` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an enum. `enumValues` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an input object. `inputFields` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: LIST
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a list. `ofType` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: NON_NULL
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a non-null. `ofType` is a valid field.

types.name: __Field
types.description: Object and Interface types are described by a list of Fields, each of which has a name, potentially a list of arguments, and a return type.

types.name: __InputValue
types.description: Arguments provided to Fields or Directives and the input fields of an InputObject are represented as Input Values which describe their type and optionally a default value.

fields.name: defaultValue
fields.description: A GraphQL-formatted string representing the default value for this input value.

types.name: __EnumValue
types.description: One possible value for a given Enum. Enum values are unique values, not a placeholder for a string or numeric value. However an Enum value is returned in a JSON response as a string.

types.name: __Directive
types.description:
A Directive provides a way to describe alternate runtime execution and type validation behavior in a GraphQL document.

In some cases, you need to provide options to alter GraphQL's execution behavior in ways field arguments will not suffice, such as conditionally including or skipping a field. Directives provide this by describing additional information to the executor.

types.name: __DirectiveLocation
types.description: A Directive can be adjacent to many parts of the GraphQL language, a __DirectiveLocation describes one such possible adjacencies.

enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a query operation.

enumValues.name: MUTATION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a mutation operation.

enumValues.name: SUBSCRIPTION

enumValues.name: FIELD

enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a fragment definition.

enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a fragment spread.

enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an inline fragment.

enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a variable definition.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a scalar definition.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an object type definition.

enumValues.name: FIELD_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a field definition.

enumValues.name: ARGUMENT_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an argument definition.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an interface definition.

enumValues.name: UNION

enumValues.name: ENUM

directives.description: Directs the executor to skip this field or fragment when the `if` argument is true.

directives.name: include

directives.description: Marks an element of a GraphQL schema as no longer supported.
